<p>N Scale &#8211; Trains are built to a ratio of 1:160. A 75-foot locomotive is approximately 5 ½ inches long. The rails of the track are spaced 9 mm apart.</p>
<p>The &#8220;gauge&#8221; is the separation of the rails.  Scale 1 / 87, 30 inch cars will run on N scale 1 / 160 track. O scale 30-inch cars run on HO track to standard gauge.</p>
<p>If you take a chance, by far the most likely scale / gauge that you will take is standard HO. Most hobby shops can tell you in an instant what you have. To measure the wheels to tell the width of the appropriate track would measure just outside the flanges of wheels. It is the internal dimension of the horizontal plane of the wheel where it sits on the rail.</p>
<p>The N-scale trains are an ideal choice for apartments or anyone with limited space. N-scale trains are easy to store when not in use and are ruggedly built for trouble-free operation. The small size is fine for teenagers and adults; younger children will need an adult to help to set up or take down a set.</p>
