      <description>O scale (or O gauge) is a scale commonly used when describing a toy train and a common size for many model railroading enthusiasts, along with the HO Scale. Originally introduced by German toy manufacturer Märklin around 1900, by the 1930s . O gauge was the most common model railroad scale in the US and [...]&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/trains-o-scale/scale-train-sets/"&gt;O Scale Train Sets&lt;/a&gt; is a post from: &lt;a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com"&gt;Trains O Scale&lt;/a&gt;:blog where you can get news on Trains O Scale and other model train collecting news.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/trains-o-scale/Trains_O_Scale-O_Scale_Train_Sets.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="attachment_4487" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 310px"><a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/oscale.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-4487" title="O Scale Train Set" src="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/oscale-300x289.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="289" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">O Scale Train Sets</p></div>
<p><strong>O scale</strong> (or <strong>O gauge</strong>) is a scale commonly used when describing a toy train and a common size for many model railroading enthusiasts, along with the HO Scale. Originally introduced by German toy manufacturer <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%A4rklin">Märklin</a> around 1900, by the 1930s . O gauge was the most common model railroad scale in the US and remained so until the early 1960s. In Europe, its popularity declined before World War 2 due to the introduction of smaller scales.</p>
<p>The Märklin specifications called for 1:43.5 scale. However, many designs were 1:48 scale or 1:64 scale.</p>
