      <title>N Scale Model Trains</title>
      <link>http://trainsoscaledepot.com/n-scale-2/scale-model-trains-4/</link>
      <comments>http://trainsoscaledepot.com/n-scale-2/scale-model-trains-4/#comments</comments>
      <pubDate>Thu, 05 Aug 2010 20:13:49 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator>Trains O Scale</dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[N Scale]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://trainsoscaledepot.com/?p=4449</guid>
      <description>For someone new to the world of model railroading, the various terms such as train, scale and gauge can appear to be quite complex. However, as one continues to delve into the wonderful hobby of model railroading, they will become second nature quite quickly. This post will feature the N Scale Model Trains. Model trains [...]&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/n-scale-2/scale-model-trains-4/"&gt;N Scale Model Trains&lt;/a&gt; is a post from: &lt;a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com"&gt;Trains O Scale&lt;/a&gt;:blog where you can get news on Trains O Scale and other model train collecting news.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/trains-o-scale/Trains_O_Scale-N_Scale_Model_Trains.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/model_train2.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-4450" title="N Scale Model Train" src="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/model_train2-300x225.jpg" alt="N Scale Model Train" width="300" height="225" /></a>For someone new to the world of model railroading, the various terms such as train, scale and gauge can appear to be quite complex. However, as one continues to delve into the wonderful hobby of model railroading, they will become second nature quite quickly. This post will feature the N Scale Model Trains.</p>
<p>Model trains come in various sizes, each of which is used for different purposes. As there are many options from which to choose, finding the one that suits you best should not be an issue.</p>
<p>Scale is the size of a model train.</p>
<p>N is the smallest among the most popular scales with a ratio of 1:160. This means that the N scale model railway is one hundred sixty times smaller than train real life. The most popular HO scale is almost twice the size of the scale N. HO scale is the ratio 1:87. N scale is for collectors of miniatures. N model trains may take less space, but the level of detail in them, according to the manufacturer remains high. One advantage with the N scale trains is that there are many accessories available which increases your chance to be creative with your layouts and overall design making it possible to create a really beautiful landscape.</p>
<p>The more popular scales are the O and HO scales which have been around for over a century. The N scales do not have the same longevity as they were created in the 60&#8242;s. The letter N stands for nine mm &#8211; in reference to the size of the meter.</p>
<p><a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/n-scale-2/scale-model-trains-4/">N Scale Model Trains</a> is a post from: <a href="http://trainsoscaledepot.com">Trains O Scale</a>:blog where you can get news on Trains O Scale and other model train collecting news.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
