<p>I have a problem that I don&#8217;t understand and I would appreciate it if you could help me with it.                                   </p>
<p> A bridge is designed with expansion joints to allow for thermal expansion. The exact length of a steel girder L mm is a linear function of the temperature T Degrees celsius.<br />
 L=mT+b<br />
a) At 5Celsius a particular girder is 9982 mm long.  At 34 celsius it is 10016 mm long.  Determine the values of M and b for this girder?<br />
b) What do M and b represent ?  Thank You very much for all the help I can get.
</p>
<p></i></p>
<p>a) At L = 9982 mm &#038; T = 5 C we get<br />
9982 = 5m + b<br />
b = 9982 &#8211; 5m<br />
At L = 10016 mm &#038; T = 34 C we get<br />
10016 = 34m + b<br />
b = 10016 &#8211; 34m</p>
<p>therefore:<br />
9982 &#8211; 5m = 10016 &#8211; 34m<br />
34m &#8211; 5m = 10016 &#8211; 9982<br />
29m = 34<br />
m = 1.17(approx.)</p>
<p>b = 10016 &#8211; 34(1.17)<br />
b = 9976.2</p>
<p>b) M represents the rate at which the temperature is increasing&#8230;.and i think the b represents the highest length of the girder <img src='http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' /><br />
