      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img style="margin-right:20px" src="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-content/uploads/Cast Metal_6.jpg" alt="Cast Metal" border="0" align="left" /></p>
<h2>The Secret of Castings</h2>
<p>Castings are produced using a manufacturing process where a liquid material is poured into a mould which has a hollow cavity of the required shape; the liquid material is then left to solidify. The solidified part is known as the casting and is then removed from the mould and this completes the process. Usually the casting materials are metals or different types of cold setting materials which cure when mixing two or more components together. Examples of these can include concrete, clay, plaster and epoxy. Casting can be used for creating simple or complex shapes that would prove difficult or uneconomical to produce by using other methods. Casting processes can be divided into two main categories: non-expendable and expendable casting.</p>
<p>There are other types of castings and casting processes and these include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ingot casting : Continuous casting : Metal casting/sand/shell casting : Shell molding : Precision casting : Gravity die casting : Pressure die casting : Centrifugal casting : Composite casting.</li>
</ul>
<p>Ingot casting is an intermediate operation between the smelting of metals and their further treatment. The metal may be cast in the form of large ingots for subsequent working by rolling, forging. stamping etc., or the castings may be smaller ingots or billets, which are more convenient to handle and are afterwards recast or are eventually formed into castings for machine parts or other components that require only a small amount of finishing treatment of one kind or another.</p>
<p>The first metal for which continuous casting was successfully employed was aluminum, which because of its low melting point and its favorable casting and solidification properties, presented the least difficulty. Vertical continuous casting is a very commonly used method for the production of ingots, tubing and other sections of this metal and its alloys.</p>
<p>Centrifugal casting is made up from a number of processes in which the centrifugal force set up by the rotation of a part of the casting installation is utilized to shape the casting, fill the mold and help solidify and strengthen the metal. There is a distinction between horizontal centrifugal casting and vertical centrifugal casting. Vertical centrifugal casting is essentially a pressure casting technique using rotation about a vertical axis. It produces good filling of the mold, a high dimensional accuracy and a high strength dense structure of the casting material. Horizontal centrifugal casting is used mainly for making long hollow castings such as tubes, pipes, gun barrels, sleeves etc. The mold rotates at high speed about a horizontal or nearly horizontal axis, the molten metal being fed into the interior of the mold and distributed around it by centrifugal action. The rotation is continued until solidification is complete. The external diameter of the casting corresponds to the internal diameter of the mold; the internal diameter of the casting can be varied by proportioning the amount and feed rate of the casting metal. An advantage of the centrifugal process is that it produces a sounder and more uniform casting than static means. The mold is usually made of steel or cast iron and non-metallic linings may be used.</p>
<p><strong>About the Author</strong><br />
</p>
<p>Anthony Pateman from RD Castings Ltd writes about <a href="http://www.rdcastings.co.uk/">Castings</a>. For more information about <a href="http://www.rdcastings.co.uk/">Castings</a> visit www.rdcastings.co.uk</p>
