      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img style="margin-right:20px" src="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-content/uploads/Gallon Tank_23.jpg" alt="Gallon Tank" border="0" align="left" /><br />
<b>will a filter from a 20 gallon fish tank work in a 40 gallon fish tank?</b><br />
<script type="text/javascript">
ch_client = "mdcson";
ch_width = 468;
ch_height = 250;
ch_type = "mpu";
ch_sid = "Trains O Scale";
ch_backfill = 1;
ch_color_site_link = "#0000CC";
ch_color_title = "#0000CC";
ch_color_border = "#FFFFFF";
ch_color_text = "#000000";
ch_color_bg = "#FFFFFF";
</script><br />
<script src="http://scripts.chitika.net/eminimalls/amm.js" type="text/javascript">
</script><br />
<i>
<p>i have a 40 gallon fish tank, and i need a filter for it. someone said they will give me theirs from their tank, but their tank is a 20 gallon tank.<br />
will it still work for mine? </p>
<p>and if not, would two 20 gallon filters work for my 40 gallon?<br />
or would i just need to get one big filter?
</p>
<p></i></p>
<p>It will &#8216;work&#8217;, as long as you dont put many fish in there.</p>
<p>The amount of filtering you need depends on the amount of fish in the tank. Bigger tanks usually have more fish, so they need bigger filters.</p>
<p>So if you set up your 40 gal, and put an undersized filter on it, you need to treat it like it&#8217;s only 20gal, and only put in 1/2 the number of fish.</p>
<p>You can allways get the tank running, cycled and get some fish in there, then buy a 2nd filter later before your fish get big, or you buy more. Simply run both filters.</p>
<p>I would suggest you make the 2nd filter a 40gal one, and use that with the 20gal for extra filtering goodness.</p>
<p>Ian</p>
