      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img style="margin-right:20px" src="http://trainsoscaledepot.com/wp-content/uploads/Gal Tank_24.jpg" alt="Gal Tank" border="0" align="left" /><br />
<b>what do i need to raise brine shimp in 10 gal tank?</b><br />
<script type="text/javascript">
ch_client = "mdcson";
ch_width = 468;
ch_height = 250;
ch_type = "mpu";
ch_sid = "Trains O Scale";
ch_backfill = 1;
ch_color_site_link = "#0000CC";
ch_color_title = "#0000CC";
ch_color_border = "#FFFFFF";
ch_color_text = "#000000";
ch_color_bg = "#FFFFFF";
</script><br />
<script src="http://scripts.chitika.net/eminimalls/amm.js" type="text/javascript">
</script><br />
<i>
<p>I want to raise brine shrimp for my fish. I have an old 10 gal tank and all the parts of a 20 gal tank i.e. filter, heater ect. What do i need to get it going and what are the specific water conditions for them to grow. If you could give me measurements for the water additives that would be great.
</p>
<p></i></p>
<p>Hey gregory, i know how to answer your question!</p>
<p>PLEASE dont choose the first person as best answer because all she did was copy and paste.</p>
<p>The truth of the matter is that raising brine shrimp is EASY.<br />
you dont even need a 10 gallon tank!!!!<br />
a 2 liter bottle works wonders.</p>
<p>Things you need:<br />
1 soda bottle<br />
1 air pump with air tube<br />
Brine shrimp eggs (sold at fish stores by the packs around 4 bucks)<br />
SALT (AQUARIUM SALT)</p>
<p>Simply add a tablespoonful of aquarium salt to the water. Also note that using fish tank water is the best. But, you can just use tap water and add water conditioner.</p>
<p>Puncture a small hole either at the top or some end&#8230; so that the eggs once added to the bottle are constantly moving with the water airline tube.</p>
<p>hatching takes 24-68 hours.</p>
<p>You usually just scoop out the brine shrimp and feed them to the tanks you have.</p>
<p>You could do it in a 10 gallon, but it&#8217;d be the same process and all youre doing is wasting water. I&#8217;d suggest a feeder farm in that 10 gallon. Using a dozen feeder guppy would turn to 100 in a month if you keep the parameters right.</p>
<p>Good luck!</p>
<p>if you need more information, feel free to email me at: rhyme2gus@gmail.com</p>
